findings.reasoning:
The `allowedUriRegexp` configuration option allows replacing the default `IS_ALLOWED_URI` pattern (`^(?:(?:f|ht)tps?|mailto|tel|callto|cid|xmpp):`) with a custom regex. In `SecureHTMLElementSanitizer.initialize()`:

```java
String configuredRegexp = this.htmlElementSanitizerConfiguration.getAllowedUriRegexp();
if (StringUtils.isNotBlank(configuredRegexp)) {
    this.allowedUriPattern = Pattern.compile(configuredRegexp, Pattern.CASE_INSENSITIVE);
}
```

If an administrator sets this to a permissive regex like `.*` or `^(javascript|data|blob):` (incorrectly attempting to block rather than allow), the sanitizer's URI validation could be completely bypassed. A misconfigured regex like `.*` would allow `javascript:` URIs to pass the `allowedUriPattern` check.

Note that `isScriptOrData()` is still checked when `allowUnknownProtocols=true`, but if a custom permissive `allowedUriPattern` matches `javascript:`, it would be allowed regardless of `allowUnknownProtocols`. The flow in `isAllowedValue()` uses short-circuit OR evaluation - once `allowedUriPattern.matcher(valueNoWhitespace).find()` returns true, the value is allowed without further checks.

This requires manual review to confirm the trust model for who can set this configuration value.

